\begin_layout Standard
An RBF network can be defined as the following function:
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y\left(\overrightarrow{x}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{k}w_{i}\phi\left(\left\Vert \overrightarrow{x}-\overrightarrow{c_{i}}\right\Vert \right)\label{eq:firstrbf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\series default
The following applies to the above equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{x}$
\end_inset

 stands for the input pattern to the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:firstrbf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The number of elements in this vector is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{c_{i}},\ i=1,..,k$
\end_inset

 are denoted as the center vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{w}$
\end_inset

 is considered as the output weight of the RBF network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The value 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(\overrightarrow{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 represents the predicted value of the network for the pattern 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Typically,
 the Gaussian function can bed used as the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 and it defined as:
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi(x)=\exp\left(-\frac{\left(x-c\right)^{2}}{\sigma^{2}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

